Basic Git Commands:



Cloning a repository:
-> git clone (HTTPS LINK)



Checking changes:
-> git status



Update changes and prepares for next commit:
-> git add --all OR git add -A
	updates everything

-> git add .
	updates only the files in the current directory

-> git add *
	updates only new or modified files, but not deleted files

-> git add *.txt, add *.exe, etc.
	updates all .txt/.exe etc. files within the current directory



Commit changes:
-> git commit -m "..."
	commits all changes adding "..." within the updated contents
 
-> git reset HEAD~
	undoes all changes made with the last commit



Delete files:
-> git rm "..."
	removes the named file

-> git rm -f "..."
	removes named file regardless of committed changes

-> git rm --cached "..."
	only removes it from staging (keeps the file in local directory)

-> git rm -r "..."
	-r means recursive, meaning any other folders/contents within the item removed will also be removed



Viewing commits:
-> git log
	shows details regarding last commits



Branching:
(Creates a "test" environment that copies the files from your main branch that allows you to test using main files)
-> git branch 
	shows all branches

-> git branch "..."
	creates a new branch with the name "..."

-> git checkout "..."
	enters the specified branch named "..."

-> git merge (branch name) -m "..."
	merges the current branch with the main branch with the ... text



Checking previous commits
-> git log --online
	Shows all previous commits along with commit ID

-> git checkout "..."
	Goes back to a previous commit with the commit ID "..."

-> git checkout main
	Goes back to last commit

-> git diff "..." "..."
	Shows the differences of both commits



Local Machine <-> Remote Repository

-> PUSH
	Sending local changes to the remote repository

-> FETCH
	Bringing remote changes into your local repository, but not merging yet

-> PULL
	Fetching and merging, so your working directly immediately reflects remote changes



-> git push origin "..."
	Pushes all changes to GitHub's remote repository, only with the specified branch "..."

-> git fetch
	Fetches new changes from the remote repository, but do not appear in your directory

-> git pull
	Fetches new changes from the remote repository, and appears within your directory



Other commands:

-> git restore
	Undoes all changes until the last commit

-> git restore --staged "..."
	Undoes all changes made within the staging area, but keeps the working directory unchanged

-> git stash
	Safely stashes your unfinished work in order to switch branches (works in a FILO stack)

-> git stash pop
	Safely retains and applies your previously stashed work

-> git stash apply
	Safely applies your previously stashed work but keeps it in the stack for future use

-> git stash list
	Shows the stack of all current stashes along with it's specific ID

-> git stash drop
	Deletes the last stash on the stack

-> git revert
	Creates a new commit that is the copy of the last commit while git reset deletes all commits previously until that last commit

-> git rebase "..."
	Moves "..."'s branch to the current branch you are in



Pull Request
-> Main idea: "I've made some changes in my branch; please review them, and if everything looks good, merge them into the main branch."

		


-> To undo the last change; -> git reset
-> To undo manually deleted files; -> git reset --hard



